[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 12.1: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 12.1. It shows one way you could translate the appointment-volume-forecasting pipeline into working Python using boto3, Prophet, and pandas. The demo generates synthetic appointment-volume data with realistic weekly seasonality, annual seasonality, holiday effects, and noise so you can see the data prep, model training, forecast generation, and DynamoDB loading work end-to-end without provisioning anything. It is not production-ready. There is no real SageMaker training job, no real Step Functions orchestration, no real EventBridge schedule, no real VPC configuration, no per-Lambda IAM least privilege, no KMS customer-managed keys, no forecast-drift monitoring, no cold-start handling for new clinics, and no hierarchical reconciliation across providers. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of a daily-volume forecasting pipeline that respects the calendar-feature discipline, the prediction-interval-not-point-estimate discipline, and the audit-everything discipline this recipe demands. It is not something you would point at a clinic staffing system on Monday morning. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You'll need the AWS SDK for Python, the Prophet forecasting library, and pandas:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3 prophet pandas
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Prophet pulls in `cmdstanpy` for the Stan backend. On first install, it may download a precompiled Stan binary. If you hit issues on ARM Macs or Linux containers, check the [Prophet installation docs](https://facebook.github.io/prophet/docs/installation.html) for platform-specific notes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject` and `s3:PutObject` on the appointment-history bucket prefix and the forecast-output prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:DescribeTrainingJob` if you move to SageMaker-hosted training
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:BatchWriteItem` and `dynamodb:PutItem` on the `appt-forecasts` table
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the KMS key protecting the S3 bucket and DynamoDB table
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things worth knowing upfront:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Appointment data is PHI by association.** Even daily aggregate counts, combined with clinic identifiers and date, can be joined back to scheduling systems that link to patient records. The S3 prefix and the DynamoDB table live under HIPAA-eligible architecture with SSE-KMS encryption, VPC endpoints, and CloudTrail audit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Prophet expects a specific DataFrame shape.** Two columns: `ds` (datestamp) and `y` (the value to forecast). Additional regressors get added as extra columns. The naming is non-negotiable; rename your data before fitting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB rejects Python `float`.** Every numeric value passes through `Decimal()` on its way into DynamoDB. The helper below handles the conversion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The prediction interval is the operational primitive.** Operations leaders staff to the upper bound, not the point estimate. Build everything around the interval, not the single number.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Everything that is configuration rather than logic lives here. In production, these would come from environment variables or SSM Parameter Store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import math
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import random
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import date, datetime, timedelta, timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from decimal import Decimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import pandas as pd
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from prophet import Prophet
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Structured logging. In production, use JSON-formatted output for
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # CloudWatch Logs Insights queries. Never log PHI field values.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Appointment counts at the aggregate daily level are borderline;
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # paired with clinic_id and date they can be correlated back to
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # scheduling records. Log structural metadata only (run_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # clinic_id, record_count, mape, runtime_ms).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Adaptive retry handles throttling from S3 and DynamoDB.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(retries={"max_attempts": 5, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Resource names (swap per environment) ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m S3_BUCKET = "appt-forecasting-data"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m S3_HISTORY_PREFIX = "history/"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m S3_FORECAST_PREFIX = "forecasts/"
